ANTHRAX, HUMAN, OVINE - BULGARIA (DOBRICH)(02): BACKGROUND
**********************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: 7 Sept 2006
From: Dr. Steve Berger <mberger@post.tau.ac.il>
Source: GIDEON [edited]
<http://www.Gideononline.com>

Regarding the recent posting on anthrax in Dobrich, it is interesting
to compare reporting trends for zoonotic diseases in this area of
Europe:
1. Rates for human anthrax and trichinosis are similar among Bulgaria
and surrounding countries:
<http://exhibit.gideononline.com/Bulgaria-anthrax.jpg> and
<http://exhibit.gideononline.com/Bulgaria-trichinosis.jpg>
2. Rates for Q-fever and Echinococcosis appear to be highest in Bulgaria
<http://exhibit.gideononline.com/Bulgaria-qfever.jpg> and
<http://exhibit.gideononline.com/Bulgaria-echinococcosis.jpg>
2. Brucellosis is most common in Macedonia
<http://exhibit.gideononline.com/Bulgaria-brucellosis.jpg>
[note: data not available for Echinococcosis in Romania and
Trichinosis in Greece]
--
Steve Berger
Geographic Medicine
Tel Aviv Medical Center
<mberger@post.tau.ac.il>
[We always appreciate the background material from GIDEON for the
perspective it adds. The graphs in the web references are excellent.
- Mod.PC]
